4
00:00:16,302 --> 00:00:18,024
and otherwise I'm just going to try to punch through it.

5
00:00:23,140 --> 00:00:27,762
My name is Colin Foran and I'm the creative lead for an internal HBO team that prototypes interactive experiences.

6
00:00:28,622 --> 00:00:32,683
My background is in art and design, first in concept art, art direction, and now creative direction.

7
00:00:33,464 --> 00:00:37,265
The HBO Interactive team is around 15 team members, all from a wide range of backgrounds.

8
00:00:37,925 --> 00:00:40,086
We're a combination of artists, designers, and engineers.

9
00:00:40,906 --> 00:00:45,147
The team has game experience from the indie through AAA space, movies, enterprise software, and so on.

10
00:00:46,800 --> 00:00:50,302
The Westworld VR Project is a really interesting cross-pollination between the game and film

11
00:00:50,342 --> 00:00:54,583
industries. This talk will broadly explore the issues that we encountered and how we

12
00:00:54,623 --> 00:00:59,665
used a combination of design and tech tools to get past them. But first, some quick background.

13
00:01:00,125 --> 00:01:04,247
When the HBO Interactive team was formed around three years ago, the task was figure out what's

14
00:01:04,267 --> 00:01:08,869
going to be interesting and then go make it. It was a very experimental, fail fast, learn

15
00:01:08,909 --> 00:01:12,170
fast team with an explicit focus on narrative. It was very important to us.

16
00:01:13,130 --> 00:01:20,693
Our jobs were to identify cool tech coming down the pipe, bang on it for a little while, and build up a little production expertise to have ready when a showrunner approached us with an idea.

17
00:01:21,253 --> 00:01:25,695
That led to a lot of greyboxing, test shoots, and demos across a handful of platforms.

18
00:01:27,136 --> 00:01:31,237
Engines and tech, not strictly VR, but always with a focus on storytelling potential.

19
00:01:31,997 --> 00:01:36,219
We were plugged into the development scene in Seattle where we were able to get our hands on VR prototypes pretty early.

20
00:01:36,979 --> 00:01:46,005
During that period, we were doing a lot with navigation, scale, tethered, untethered, stylization versus realism, showing player body, all the usual suspects that I'm sure will be familiar to everyone in here.

21
00:01:47,065 --> 00:01:52,388
At the same time, we were building relationships with the showrunner staff and getting up to speed on how the rest of HBO's content is produced.

22
00:01:53,009 --> 00:01:58,032
Different productions are siloed from one another, so we spent a lot of our early days banging on doors and introducing ourselves to people.

23
00:01:58,947 --> 00:02:02,450
That turned into months of roadshows, showcasing our early demos and VR work.

24
00:02:03,110 --> 00:02:05,872
We call it VRpalooza, and that started around December of 2014.

25
00:02:05,952 --> 00:02:09,875
We found a show-don't-tell approach worked best,

26
00:02:10,315 --> 00:02:12,557
so our demos started looking pretty sophisticated.

27
00:02:13,237 --> 00:02:16,179
Not quite vertical slices, but with a certain degree of polish for sure.

28
00:02:17,093 --> 00:02:22,538
We had a broad range of people and partners and were able to drum up a lot of internal interest around HBO's potential spin on VR,

29
00:02:22,939 --> 00:02:25,721
specifically trying to advance the state of character-based storytelling.

30
00:02:26,322 --> 00:02:29,445
But we knew a lot of thought had to go into the stories that would feel appropriate to the platform.

31
00:02:30,045 --> 00:02:33,729
After a final round of internal demos, we were encouraged to meet with the Westworld showrunners.

32
00:02:34,672 --> 00:02:37,093
We met Jonah Nolan and Lisa Joy in June of 2015.

33
00:02:37,554 --> 00:02:41,156
They explained that the series would be about having your perceptions manipulated

34
00:02:41,236 --> 00:02:43,578
and the effects that could have on a person in a controlled environment.

35
00:02:44,198 --> 00:02:47,360
The idea of doing that from a first-person perspective was fascinating to everyone

36
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:48,982
and the pitch came together fairly quickly.

37
00:02:49,482 --> 00:02:52,104
That kicked off about a year's worth of focused prototyping and development.

38
00:02:53,004 --> 00:02:55,247
That started a surprisingly open working relationship.

39
00:02:55,948 --> 00:02:57,730
Throughout development, we worked closely with the show's

40
00:02:57,770 --> 00:02:59,972
writers, production staff, and the show runners themselves to

41
00:03:00,012 --> 00:03:01,013
ensure we were making something

42
00:03:01,053 --> 00:03:02,174
interesting and true to the show.

43
00:03:02,875 --> 00:03:04,337
Now we needed to figure out what we wanted to make.

44
00:03:05,358 --> 00:03:05,818
So what is it?

45
00:03:06,634 --> 00:03:11,217
Westworld VR is a multi-format, room-scale, destination experience in three-ish parts,

46
00:03:11,598 --> 00:03:13,399
with a strong focus on narrative and character.

47
00:03:13,899 --> 00:03:16,661
We debuted the experience at TechCrunch shortly before the show premiered.

48
00:03:17,402 --> 00:03:21,725
It combines room-scale real-time content, 360 video, physical props,

49
00:03:21,865 --> 00:03:24,467
and an in-universe physical build-out staffed by actors.

50
00:03:25,267 --> 00:03:30,291
The story itself was written with the Westworld showrunners and writing staff and created interesting challenges for the team to tease out.

51
00:03:30,831 --> 00:03:36,234
Meaningful character interaction in VR, onset 360 capture that progressed the story and felt true to the show,

52
00:03:36,715 --> 00:03:42,799
as well as traditionally difficult film set challenges like, for example, micing naked actors doing stunt shoots.

53
00:03:43,699 --> 00:03:49,643
Any one of those on their own would be challenging and combining them in a way that felt coherent and really contributed to the story made it even more so.

54
00:03:50,244 --> 00:03:51,805
So let me walk you through the user experience.

55
00:03:53,126 --> 00:03:55,927
The user is greeted by actors at an in-universe Delos pop-up

56
00:03:55,967 --> 00:03:56,508
installation.

57
00:03:56,748 --> 00:03:58,929
They create a reservation and spend some time chatting with

58
00:03:58,949 --> 00:03:59,409
the actors.

59
00:04:00,089 --> 00:04:02,410
When the reservation is ready, they're taken to a back room

60
00:04:02,430 --> 00:04:04,611
staffed by Delos tech personnel to gear up and

61
00:04:04,631 --> 00:04:05,032
headset.

62
00:04:06,532 --> 00:04:08,953
Once they're acclimated to the equipment using an in-headset

63
00:04:09,014 --> 00:04:10,894
lobby area, they're transported to the Delos

64
00:04:10,934 --> 00:04:13,596
dressing room and greeted by a park host that they had chosen

65
00:04:13,816 --> 00:04:15,016
earlier during the reservation.

66
00:04:15,917 --> 00:04:17,538
The host is preserved throughout the duration of the

67
00:04:17,578 --> 00:04:18,018
experience.

68
00:04:19,869 --> 00:04:21,810
After the user gets some brief narrative background,

69
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:23,871
the rules of the park and selects a weapon,

70
00:04:25,192 --> 00:04:27,293
they transition into the interior of the park itself.

71
00:04:29,054 --> 00:04:30,295
A little more background is sprinkled

72
00:04:30,315 --> 00:04:31,635
into the conversation with the host

73
00:04:31,735 --> 00:04:34,137
and the user gets to do some light exploration of the space

74
00:04:35,178 --> 00:04:35,998
as well as some shooting.

75
00:04:37,919 --> 00:04:39,360
A quest giver NPC appears.

76
00:04:39,620 --> 00:04:41,141
In the fiction of the show, it's the sheriff

77
00:04:41,921 --> 00:04:43,502
and he attempts to enlist the user's help

78
00:04:43,522 --> 00:04:45,023
to track down Hector Escaton.

79
00:04:46,607 --> 00:04:48,872
Mid-delivery, a fly, which will be familiar to viewers of

80
00:04:48,892 --> 00:04:51,338
this show, lands on the sheriff's face, triggering an

81
00:04:51,418 --> 00:04:52,541
error in the host programming.

82
00:04:53,002 --> 00:04:55,688
They turn homicidal, executing your host, and

83
00:04:55,728 --> 00:04:56,730
eventually turning on you.

84
00:04:58,283 --> 00:05:01,987
The player wakes up to a semi-conscious state surrounded by lab techs and equipment, where

85
00:05:02,007 --> 00:05:03,648
they're urged to sit down in a physical chair.

86
00:05:04,108 --> 00:05:08,932
This abstract chapter serves as our transition from real-time to 360 content, and then the

87
00:05:08,972 --> 00:05:11,815
corresponding transition from fully interactive to zero interactivity.

88
00:05:12,555 --> 00:05:16,338
Finally they awaken in the Delos lab, revealing that they are, in fact, hosts themselves.

89
00:05:16,919 --> 00:05:21,503
After being wheeled through the lab, their companion host wakes up, attacking their captors

90
00:05:21,523 --> 00:05:24,745
and imploring the user to remember what has happened before all kinds of horrible things

91
00:05:24,765 --> 00:05:25,046
happen.

92
00:05:25,486 --> 00:05:26,106
And it's lights out.

93
00:05:27,376 --> 00:05:31,657
It was also a test to see how effectively HBO Interactive and the Westworld production teams could mesh pipelines.

94
00:05:32,197 --> 00:05:36,439
This wasn't simply two production teams sharing assets, this was a fundamental meshing of working styles.

95
00:05:36,899 --> 00:05:40,440
Writers, actors, asset creators, and producers all learning to speak the same language.

96
00:05:41,100 --> 00:05:45,661
Interactive tools and their advantages are foreign to many of the production teams, because of course they are, they're different industries.

97
00:05:46,382 --> 00:05:52,123
Most of our group comes from AAA gaming, and so we had a responsibility to educate and show by example what these technologies could do.

98
00:05:53,191 --> 00:05:55,192
High-end game and show productions are very different,

99
00:05:55,312 --> 00:05:57,574
but there's enough of a shared vocabulary with slightly

100
00:05:57,614 --> 00:05:59,635
different meanings that it's easy for misunderstandings to

101
00:05:59,675 --> 00:06:00,055
pop up.

102
00:06:01,336 --> 00:06:02,537
So what were we trying to accomplish?

103
00:06:03,077 --> 00:06:05,078
This isn't a comprehensive list, but an idea of what we

104
00:06:05,098 --> 00:06:05,599
were aiming for.

105
00:06:06,653 --> 00:06:08,734
What are questions that, if left unanswered, could

106
00:06:08,794 --> 00:06:10,854
compromise our ability to work with future showrunners?

107
00:06:11,615 --> 00:06:13,655
For me, this was a vehicle to show that the technology was

108
00:06:13,695 --> 00:06:15,455
ready for mature, complicated stories.

109
00:06:15,916 --> 00:06:18,176
People needed to look at it as an example and have no doubt

110
00:06:18,216 --> 00:06:19,316
that, yes, they could tell their

111
00:06:19,336 --> 00:06:20,417
stories using this medium.

112
00:06:21,017 --> 00:06:22,917
But that's actually a pretty ambitious statement.

113
00:06:23,117 --> 00:06:25,078
There are a ton of things wrapped up in that concept.

114
00:06:25,638 --> 00:06:27,738
I tried to imagine questions coming from the showrunners.

115
00:06:28,158 --> 00:06:29,679
Can I put one of my actors in this thing?

116
00:06:29,859 --> 00:06:31,139
Can they give a meaningful performance?

117
00:06:31,339 --> 00:06:32,139
How do I move around?

118
00:06:32,619 --> 00:06:34,260
I know that I can't force people to look at what I want

119
00:06:34,280 --> 00:06:36,140
them to, so prove to me that that doesn't matter.

120
00:06:36,762 --> 00:06:39,781
Anything we could do to prepare ourselves for future meetings and speak with confidence.

121
00:06:41,464 --> 00:06:43,685
At a high level, it was simply building production confidence.

122
00:06:44,046 --> 00:06:46,328
Based on our experiments, we could project outward and say

123
00:06:46,388 --> 00:06:47,869
that we could make some of this stuff.

124
00:06:48,349 --> 00:06:50,071
But there was nothing that we could point to definitively

125
00:06:50,111 --> 00:06:51,252
and say, it'll be like that.

126
00:06:51,672 --> 00:06:52,893
We had to build up a ton of trust.

127
00:06:53,534 --> 00:06:55,435
We also needed to test our game design theories in a

128
00:06:55,475 --> 00:06:56,296
production environment.

129
00:06:56,756 --> 00:06:58,198
Not to belabor the point, but remember, these

130
00:06:58,218 --> 00:06:59,038
were the early days.

131
00:06:59,499 --> 00:07:01,180
We were past the point of knowing that, yes, we could

132
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:02,201
technically do something.

133
00:07:02,561 --> 00:07:04,223
But from a narrative perspective, should we?

134
00:07:04,763 --> 00:07:06,665
The team was excited to roll these disparate demos and

135
00:07:06,685 --> 00:07:08,446
experiments into something that felt significant.

136
00:07:08,987 --> 00:07:11,148
We got a ton of mileage out of our gray box work, but this

137
00:07:11,168 --> 00:07:12,669
was a chance to really stress our ideas.

138
00:07:13,149 --> 00:07:15,190
There's a lot to try, from navigation, affordance,

139
00:07:15,270 --> 00:07:17,531
chapter length, transition intensity, and so on.

140
00:07:18,111 --> 00:07:20,513
We certainly weren't the first to be thinking about these

141
00:07:20,573 --> 00:07:22,554
ideas, but we had never seen an experience that put them

142
00:07:22,574 --> 00:07:23,854
all together in the way that we wanted.

143
00:07:24,715 --> 00:07:26,736
We also wanted a gesture towards what a high production

144
00:07:26,756 --> 00:07:29,297
value experience could look like by using design tricks

145
00:07:29,337 --> 00:07:31,278
and misdirection to punch above our weight a little bit.

146
00:07:31,738 --> 00:07:33,820
We were a small team attempting to show what a

147
00:07:33,880 --> 00:07:35,220
larger team could potentially do.

148
00:07:38,354 --> 00:07:40,255
From an environment art standpoint, that meant working

149
00:07:40,275 --> 00:07:42,315
hard to imply that there was more of a world to explore

150
00:07:42,355 --> 00:07:44,496
just around the corner, or to use dramatic lighting and

151
00:07:44,676 --> 00:07:46,977
suggest more mystery and depth while obscuring our

152
00:07:46,997 --> 00:07:47,877
production limitations.

153
00:07:48,837 --> 00:07:51,118
We had similar ideas on the character side, that if users

154
00:07:51,158 --> 00:07:53,179
tested an interaction with a character, they would get a

155
00:07:53,219 --> 00:07:55,279
response implying that there was a ton of robustness behind

156
00:07:55,299 --> 00:07:55,799
that character.

157
00:07:56,220 --> 00:07:58,440
If I tried to shoot my host, for example, they would

158
00:07:58,460 --> 00:07:59,480
acknowledge it and respond.

159
00:07:59,901 --> 00:08:01,861
But there's only so far you can walk down that road before

160
00:08:01,881 --> 00:08:02,962
hitting production limitations.

161
00:08:04,350 --> 00:08:06,471
Which is a good time for an aside, the first of many.

162
00:08:07,392 --> 00:08:08,772
Know what you're making and for whom.

163
00:08:09,312 --> 00:08:11,213
You'll hear me say this a few more times, but I think it's

164
00:08:11,253 --> 00:08:13,954
important to take away, or it's an important takeaway that we

165
00:08:13,974 --> 00:08:14,934
only learned with hindsight.

166
00:08:15,455 --> 00:08:17,695
In the example I just gave, we spent a huge amount of time

