236
00:11:09,157 --> 00:11:10,378
location that responds to them.

237
00:11:10,878 --> 00:11:13,180
We are always faithful to the Westworld story as defined by

238
00:11:13,220 --> 00:11:13,861
the writing team.

239
00:11:13,981 --> 00:11:14,921
That comes up later.

240
00:11:15,682 --> 00:11:17,864
Headset-centric content creation on the production

241
00:11:17,904 --> 00:11:20,126
side, thoughtfully target fidelity to an

242
00:11:20,226 --> 00:11:21,247
asset or video's use.

243
00:11:21,687 --> 00:11:23,889
Asset detail increases or falls off with proximity to

244
00:11:23,909 --> 00:11:24,249
the player.

245
00:11:24,990 --> 00:11:26,790
And sets our stage to maintain viewer interest.

246
00:11:27,130 --> 00:11:29,431
As much as possible, we don't author or capture detail that

247
00:11:29,451 --> 00:11:30,431
will be lost in the headset.

248
00:11:30,951 --> 00:11:33,012
Within the limitations of our hardware, we are targeting

249
00:11:33,052 --> 00:11:35,312
realistic real-time scenes and high-definition video

250
00:11:35,332 --> 00:11:38,573
capture, all of which sounds very obvious, but at the time

251
00:11:38,613 --> 00:11:39,293
we struggled with it.

252
00:11:40,673 --> 00:11:41,253
So how did it go?

253
00:11:41,753 --> 00:11:42,654
What landed and what didn't?

254
00:11:44,454 --> 00:11:46,254
Before we touch on anything else, we need to start with

255
00:11:46,294 --> 00:11:46,875
communication.

256
00:11:47,788 --> 00:11:50,111
One principle we continually return to was delivering in

257
00:11:50,131 --> 00:11:51,193
the spirit of the request.

258
00:11:51,714 --> 00:11:53,416
There were times that, because of our lack of shared

259
00:11:53,436 --> 00:11:55,459
vocabulary, the showrunners would ask for something that

260
00:11:55,479 --> 00:11:56,761
would completely freak out our team.

261
00:11:57,362 --> 00:11:59,304
It was important during those moments to step back and say,

262
00:11:59,365 --> 00:12:01,788
all right, we know we can't literally do this thing, but

263
00:12:01,828 --> 00:12:03,310
how can we deliver in the spirit of the thing?

264
00:12:03,931 --> 00:12:09,535
The best example of this was a request from the writers to have users manhandled by lab techs during the transition from interactive to video,

265
00:12:10,015 --> 00:12:12,116
actually having an actor tech force you into a seat.

266
00:12:12,657 --> 00:12:18,140
That was a non-starter for a handful of reasons, but it was important to dig into the emotional response that they were searching for with that request.

267
00:12:18,681 --> 00:12:22,603
The idea of uncertainty or helplessness was absolutely appropriate for the story at that point.

268
00:12:23,063 --> 00:12:28,827
We were able to target that in a way that respected user comfort in the overall safety contract the user has with the people running the installation.

269
00:12:31,238 --> 00:12:32,758
Similarly, there were a handful of times where our

270
00:12:32,798 --> 00:12:34,299
production wires simply got crossed.

271
00:12:34,579 --> 00:12:36,740
A request would come in, for example, to change an outfit.

272
00:12:37,400 --> 00:12:39,740
As an art lead, my mind went immediately to a game-centric

273
00:12:39,840 --> 00:12:41,741
pipeline ramification mode.

274
00:12:42,181 --> 00:12:43,922
How could I explain that if we took the time to change an

275
00:12:43,962 --> 00:12:45,962
outfit, none of our characters would have hair because the

276
00:12:46,002 --> 00:12:48,783
same artist was responsible for both, when in reality, the

277
00:12:48,823 --> 00:12:51,164
comment may simply be, the characters are looking kind of

278
00:12:51,204 --> 00:12:53,825
samey, which is totally valid and much simpler to fix.

279
00:12:54,285 --> 00:12:55,705
Tweak some color blocking, and you're good to go.

280
00:12:56,649 --> 00:12:58,853
And frankly, the show staff are very, very smart people.

281
00:12:59,013 --> 00:13:01,117
They have great ideas and knew the source content way better

282
00:13:01,157 --> 00:13:01,879
than we ever could.

283
00:13:02,380 --> 00:13:04,384
If you get too caught up in production minutia, you risk

284
00:13:04,785 --> 00:13:06,247
missing out on some really interesting ideas.

285
00:13:07,630 --> 00:13:08,271
Aside number two.

286
00:13:09,331 --> 00:13:11,673
A challenge we had early on was the show defining real.

287
00:13:12,093 --> 00:13:14,174
Real on this platform is a pretty loaded word.

288
00:13:14,675 --> 00:13:18,797
I'm sure most of the people in this room equate real with a feeling of presence that we haven't seen in games before.

289
00:13:19,378 --> 00:13:20,618
Real for the show meant video.

290
00:13:20,859 --> 00:13:25,502
It was the truest possible representation of an actor's performance, which was the most important thing that they wanted to preserve.

291
00:13:26,042 --> 00:13:30,545
There was also a feeling that no matter how good our assets looked, they would never look as good as the real footage.

292
00:13:31,287 --> 00:13:33,349
We actually did a fair amount of R&D before committing to

293
00:13:33,369 --> 00:13:34,190
real-time characters.

294
00:13:34,331 --> 00:13:35,632
We did a handful of experiments around

295
00:13:35,652 --> 00:13:37,615
stereoscopic billboards and volumetric video.

296
00:13:38,135 --> 00:13:39,898
But there were issues around hitting the quality level we

297
00:13:39,918 --> 00:13:41,019
were looking for in the various

298
00:13:41,059 --> 00:13:42,080
performance considerations.

299
00:13:42,902 --> 00:13:44,664
It was really track controllers that won the day

300
00:13:44,684 --> 00:13:45,164
for real-time.

301
00:13:46,187 --> 00:13:49,550
We had to spend a lot of time making the case that internal consistency in an environment

302
00:13:49,590 --> 00:13:51,312
was more important than surface level fidelity.

303
00:13:51,873 --> 00:13:55,516
If we dropped a prerecorded stereo billboard into a real-time scene, it wouldn't matter

304
00:13:55,536 --> 00:13:58,799
that the performance you captured was more real, it wouldn't cohese with the rest of

305
00:13:58,819 --> 00:14:00,801
the scene and only serve to pull you out of the experience.

306
00:14:01,281 --> 00:14:03,964
But that brings us back to working towards the spirit of the request.

307
00:14:04,444 --> 00:14:06,766
What they were after was nuanced, humanistic performance.

308
00:14:07,207 --> 00:14:10,049
Once we proved we could do that within the limitations of the platform, we had them on

309
00:14:10,110 --> 00:14:10,290
board.

310
00:14:11,150 --> 00:14:12,731
That's not to say we didn't find a ton of value in

311
00:14:12,751 --> 00:14:13,551
experimenting, though.

312
00:14:14,071 --> 00:14:15,372
We did a lot of experimentation around

313
00:14:15,412 --> 00:14:17,533
different ways to get video into the experience, but

314
00:14:17,553 --> 00:14:19,233
that's when you need the production discipline to say,

315
00:14:19,353 --> 00:14:20,654
no, let's revisit the pillars.

316
00:14:21,334 --> 00:14:23,215
The billboard environments we did were cool, and there was

317
00:14:23,235 --> 00:14:25,316
probably a satisfying Westworld experience in there

318
00:14:25,336 --> 00:14:27,496
somewhere, but in the context of our pillars, they just

319
00:14:27,516 --> 00:14:28,617
weren't right for the experience.

320
00:14:29,237 --> 00:14:31,458
That, I know it might not work, but let's try it anyway

321
00:14:31,498 --> 00:14:33,879
to see if anything interesting falls out, is a very cool way

322
00:14:33,919 --> 00:14:35,399
to work, if not a little spooky from a

323
00:14:35,419 --> 00:14:36,220
production perspective.

324
00:14:37,912 --> 00:14:39,673
So with that out of the way, we can talk nuts and bolts.

325
00:14:40,273 --> 00:14:42,294
Our interactive pipeline would be familiar to anyone here.

326
00:14:42,634 --> 00:14:45,135
Storyboarding, concept art, modeling, PBR texturing,

327
00:14:45,175 --> 00:14:46,895
integration into the engine, so on and so on.

328
00:14:47,476 --> 00:14:49,576
The only real hiccup here was recalibrating to our fairly

329
00:14:49,596 --> 00:14:50,797
aggressive hardware limitations.

330
00:14:51,377 --> 00:14:53,037
We tried to get around that by building out beautiful

331
00:14:53,077 --> 00:14:55,278
corners and vertical slices to aggressively zero in on

332
00:14:55,318 --> 00:14:56,179
appropriate fidelity.

333
00:14:56,719 --> 00:14:58,479
It takes a little bit longer in the beginning, but it's

334
00:14:58,499 --> 00:14:58,919
worth doing.

335
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:01,280
If things got too heavy, they got triaged out.

336
00:15:03,270 --> 00:15:05,252
Digital doubles and their blends were hand sculpted.

337
00:15:05,692 --> 00:15:07,754
I did not write a what I would do differently section,

338
00:15:07,774 --> 00:15:10,777
but if I did, I would say that we would almost certainly use scans going forward.

339
00:15:11,197 --> 00:15:13,219
It was a significant production hit.

340
00:15:14,060 --> 00:15:17,623
In general, quality increased over time as Epic made continual optimizations to the engine.

341
00:15:19,244 --> 00:15:22,427
Props and environments went through a familiar process, concept, model, texture, etc.

342
00:15:23,346 --> 00:15:26,587
There are a lot of interesting design conversations around what to keep faithful to reality and

343
00:15:26,607 --> 00:15:29,409
what to exaggerate for the sake of drama or wow factor in VR.

344
00:15:29,989 --> 00:15:34,291
In the case of this revolver, it's like this big, but it feels cooler to feel in the headset.

345
00:15:34,311 --> 00:15:37,272
Some more environment art.

346
00:15:39,793 --> 00:15:40,973
Some more VFX dev look.

347
00:15:43,584 --> 00:15:45,647
Animation was our long pole and would continue to cause

348
00:15:45,667 --> 00:15:46,688
headaches throughout the production.

349
00:15:47,188 --> 00:15:49,231
We used mocap for face and bodies and continually

350
00:15:49,271 --> 00:15:50,933
struggled with how to incorporate edits from the

351
00:15:50,973 --> 00:15:53,035
show writers as well as achieve a humanistic feeling

352
00:15:53,055 --> 00:15:54,096
of interactivity with the hosts.

353
00:15:54,597 --> 00:15:55,918
One always seemed to damage the other.

354
00:15:56,819 --> 00:15:58,000
And there are two elements to that, I think.

355
00:15:58,807 --> 00:16:00,728
One was our trying to build in more animation robustness

356
00:16:00,748 --> 00:16:01,248
than we needed.

357
00:16:01,688 --> 00:16:03,269
That goes back to the know what it is you're making

358
00:16:03,309 --> 00:16:04,009
point from earlier.

359
00:16:04,749 --> 00:16:06,270
The other was not having a solid solution for

360
00:16:06,310 --> 00:16:08,891
incorporating notes and feedback from the performance

361
00:16:08,911 --> 00:16:09,351
from the show.

362
00:16:10,032 --> 00:16:12,393
Our desire to show, not tell for the writers was directly

363
00:16:12,433 --> 00:16:13,693
at odds with our mocap pipeline.

364
00:16:14,153 --> 00:16:16,094
We were able to fake it a little bit with hand animation,

365
00:16:16,294 --> 00:16:18,756
asset store assets, and in-house grungy mocap, but

366
00:16:18,776 --> 00:16:19,736
that only got us so far.

367
00:16:20,236 --> 00:16:22,117
We wouldn't be able to really evaluate our performances

368
00:16:22,157 --> 00:16:23,298
until fairly late in the project.

369
00:16:24,029 --> 00:16:25,009
And I don't know a way around that.

370
00:16:25,570 --> 00:16:27,791
We did loads of storyboarding and block out and headset, but

371
00:16:27,831 --> 00:16:29,653
sometimes you just can't make a call until you see it.

372
00:16:30,593 --> 00:16:32,095
A similar thing can be said for ADR.

373
00:16:32,415 --> 00:16:33,936
There were certain bits of dialogue we just couldn't

374
00:16:33,956 --> 00:16:35,617
evaluate until we heard it all in context.

375
00:16:36,158 --> 00:16:38,299
We should have planned for the need to do a full ADR session

376
00:16:38,339 --> 00:16:39,921
from the beginning, but we let it surprise us.

377
00:16:40,041 --> 00:16:41,622
And I think that's my takeaway from the whole thing.

378
00:16:42,302 --> 00:16:44,544
In the end, we over-engineered some things while allowing

379
00:16:44,584 --> 00:16:45,885
ourselves to be surprised by others.

380
00:16:47,806 --> 00:16:48,567
Anecdote time again.

381
00:16:49,668 --> 00:16:51,970
Bandits versus Sheriff, aggressively cutting things

382
00:16:52,010 --> 00:16:52,510
that don't work.

383
00:16:53,453 --> 00:16:55,974
Originally, you had the user attacked by two bandits that

384
00:16:56,014 --> 00:16:58,255
rode onto the bluff, menaced the roadhouse, and murdered

385
00:16:58,275 --> 00:16:58,715
the players.

386
00:16:59,375 --> 00:17:01,136
We wanted to capitalize on scenes from the show.

387
00:17:01,736 --> 00:17:03,657
A user would point their gun at the bandits, fire, and

388
00:17:03,697 --> 00:17:04,357
nothing would happen.

389
00:17:04,757 --> 00:17:06,418
That was originally the point at which the user would

390
00:17:06,438 --> 00:17:07,978
understand that they were, in fact, a host.

391
00:17:08,839 --> 00:17:10,859
Bandits felt like a satisfying mission setup, but it was

392
00:17:10,899 --> 00:17:11,640
confusing to people.

393
00:17:12,080 --> 00:17:13,120
Why couldn't I shoot the bandits?

394
00:17:13,300 --> 00:17:14,321
Did I do something wrong?

395
00:17:14,441 --> 00:17:16,421
I tried reloading the gun, and it would let me, et cetera,

396
00:17:16,441 --> 00:17:16,781
et cetera.

397
00:17:17,602 --> 00:17:21,923
The bandits weren't working and no matter how many small tweaks or adjustments we made we couldn't get them to read correctly.

398
00:17:22,303 --> 00:17:23,703
So we did a script rewrite and cut them.

399
00:17:24,484 --> 00:17:25,984
We replaced them with our kindly sheriff.

400
00:17:26,564 --> 00:17:28,665
Whether people recognize the character from the show or not,

401
00:17:29,005 --> 00:17:33,886
we could rely on the symbol of a sheriff and the benevolence implied there to more clearly convey the state change to the viewer

402
00:17:33,906 --> 00:17:35,046
when the fly lands on his face.

403
00:17:36,047 --> 00:17:39,948
It was really challenging to cut that much content, especially the mocap,

404
00:17:39,968 --> 00:17:42,148
from the experience, but it had to be done for clarity's sake.

405
00:17:44,584 --> 00:17:45,024
Affordance.

406
00:17:45,464 --> 00:17:46,905
We spent a lot of time throughout the project

407
00:17:46,945 --> 00:17:49,067
developing a strategy around the dividing line between

408
00:17:49,107 --> 00:17:51,769
traditional game UX and game design object interaction.

409
00:17:52,550 --> 00:17:54,952
There was a lot of design and conversation around gamey user

410
00:17:54,972 --> 00:17:57,114
communication, like glowing outlines on interactive

411
00:17:57,194 --> 00:17:59,135
objects versus trying to keep things discoverable.

412
00:17:59,764 --> 00:18:02,305
In the end, we tried for physical where possible, but

413
00:18:02,345 --> 00:18:04,487
if an interaction was worse without explicit call-outs,

414
00:18:04,847 --> 00:18:05,608
then we would put them in.

415
00:18:06,268 --> 00:18:08,010
I wish it was cleaner than that, but there you go.

416
00:18:08,950 --> 00:18:11,032
Another benefit of the experience as a destination is

417
00:18:11,052 --> 00:18:13,073
that we had total control over the user experience.

418
00:18:13,674 --> 00:18:15,515
It didn't end up happening, but if we ever got into a

419
00:18:15,535 --> 00:18:17,777
situation where someone simply wasn't getting an interaction

420
00:18:17,797 --> 00:18:20,399
or becoming stuck, we knew we had the actors available to

421
00:18:20,419 --> 00:18:22,400
provide feedback or guidance through a microphone.

422
00:18:22,840 --> 00:18:25,042
That kept us from having to rely too heavily on voiceover,

423
00:18:25,102 --> 00:18:26,163
text overlay, et cetera.

424
00:18:27,778 --> 00:18:30,398
In the headset or it doesn't count.

425
00:18:30,838 --> 00:18:33,019
It was kind of incredible how often we would land on a design

426
00:18:33,059 --> 00:18:35,439
idea that we were totally confident in, only to have it

427
00:18:35,479 --> 00:18:36,780
fall down once it was in the headset.

428
00:18:37,260 --> 00:18:39,460
That also taught us not to get too precious with our ideas.

429
00:18:39,840 --> 00:18:41,320
If the wine is bad, spit it out.

430
00:18:42,261 --> 00:18:44,261
That applied to the general environment layout as well.

431
00:18:44,741 --> 00:18:46,961
We spent a lot of time with a variety of gray box testing

432
00:18:46,981 --> 00:18:48,542
whether or not an environment should match the show

433
00:18:48,602 --> 00:18:50,902
perfectly or be altered drastically to meet the

434
00:18:50,922 --> 00:18:53,003
physical borders of the play volume, or be some

435
00:18:53,043 --> 00:18:53,783
combination of the two.

436
00:18:54,981 --> 00:18:56,542
And in general, we struggled with affordance.

437
00:18:57,042 --> 00:18:58,984
We had the general design challenge of wanting items to

438
00:18:59,024 --> 00:19:00,826
behave as you'd expect them to in the real world.

439
00:19:01,326 --> 00:19:03,208
We were able to solve for a lot of that by keeping things

440
00:19:03,268 --> 00:19:05,530
just out of reach and implying that they could be interacted

441
00:19:05,590 --> 00:19:05,710
with.

442
00:19:06,591 --> 00:19:08,713
I worried about that approach early on, but people bought

443
00:19:08,733 --> 00:19:09,794
into it without any problems.

444
00:19:11,959 --> 00:19:15,384
The chute. Our chute took place on location in the Delos lab set.

445
00:19:16,325 --> 00:19:19,549
I don't think I've ever seen a location more hostile to the idea of a 360 chute.

446
00:19:20,471 --> 00:19:27,220
Rectilinear patterns everywhere, nested reflected surfaces, tight corridors, and dramatic lighting all promise to make stitching and processing a nightmare.

447
00:19:28,117 --> 00:19:31,562
Thankfully, we had the support of Spherica for capture and processing, and the Westworld

448
00:19:31,582 --> 00:19:33,484
production team for set support on the data chute.

449
00:19:34,185 --> 00:19:37,610
Of course, lighting, sound, and blocking all had to be approached differently, and watching

450
00:19:37,630 --> 00:19:41,094
the department leads solve these problems, often for the first time, was very impressive.

451
00:19:41,936 --> 00:19:43,097
Sometimes we just had to improvise.

452
00:19:43,718 --> 00:19:45,959
For this shoot, we didn't hire a director of photography.

453
00:19:46,119 --> 00:19:47,820
Rather, I was on set explaining what we needed

454
00:19:47,860 --> 00:19:49,721
different elements of the shot to do, and then we blocked the

455
00:19:49,741 --> 00:19:50,381
set accordingly.

456
00:19:51,041 --> 00:19:53,082
They came together, but some issues were more difficult to

457
00:19:53,122 --> 00:19:53,783
address than others.

458
00:19:54,483 --> 00:19:56,864
For example, we had to move Video Village off set, but due

459
00:19:56,904 --> 00:19:59,285
to the range, the monitors we were using continually ran in

460
00:19:59,325 --> 00:20:00,426
a wireless signal drop-off.

461
00:20:00,986 --> 00:20:02,967
Eventually, we were able to duct tape a solution together,

462
00:20:03,367 --> 00:20:05,128
but it's those sorts of issues you won't see coming until

463
00:20:05,148 --> 00:20:05,768
you're in the middle of it.

464
00:20:08,262 --> 00:20:13,204
The group had done a lot of experimentation with mono and stereo 360 video before, but this was on a totally different scale.

465
00:20:13,865 --> 00:20:18,947
We spent a ton of time both before and on the day of the rehearsals experimenting with single shots, crossfades, and so on.

466
00:20:19,547 --> 00:20:22,948
We were terrified of introducing nausea, but in the end we were being too conservative.

467
00:20:23,508 --> 00:20:26,390
Eventually the director made a hard push for the one long continuous shot.

468
00:20:27,053 --> 00:20:28,714
with all of the turns involved with that.

469
00:20:29,234 --> 00:20:31,515
We were spooked, but found that if you were gradual enough in

470
00:20:31,535 --> 00:20:33,276
your movements, we didn't introduce any discomfort.

471
00:20:33,836 --> 00:20:35,777
We also had the wheelchair follow the outside of the

472
00:20:35,817 --> 00:20:37,878
room, meaning that the user always had a dark wall to one

473
00:20:37,918 --> 00:20:39,359
side of them for most of the trip.

474
00:20:39,939 --> 00:20:42,141
That had the double benefit of allowing us to block action

475
00:20:42,181 --> 00:20:44,762
and guide gaze, as well as give users some visual rest if

476
00:20:44,782 --> 00:20:45,202
they needed it.

477
00:20:48,147 --> 00:20:51,708
And then there were the typical issues that you would run into on any production, but were new to our team.

478
00:20:52,328 --> 00:20:53,689
Casting was especially difficult.

479
00:20:54,209 --> 00:20:59,250
I had worked with actors in games to capture a likeness, but the contract negotiations around live-action casting were new to me.

480
00:20:59,710 --> 00:21:07,092
